         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0644">
               <p>Converted under <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2221.xml"/>George
                     Whitefield</persName> in <placeName>Ireland</placeName>, Edwards became a lay
                  preacher in <date when="1745">1745</date> and a <seg ana="itinerancy">traveling
                     preacher</seg> in <date when="1747">1747</date>. He had successful ministries
                  in <placeName>Dublin</placeName> and <placeName>Limerick</placeName>, and then in
                     <placeName>England</placeName>. But by the mid <date>1750s</date> he was
                  chafing under <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s
                  control of the <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerants</seg>, the restriction of lay
                  preachers from the sacramental office, and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s Arminian theology.
                  Assigned the <placeName>Leeds</placeName> circuit in <date when="1754"
                  >1754</date>, at the end of the <date when="1755">1755</date> Conference Edwards
                  refused to move, taking many in the society with him to form an Independent
                  congregation that built White Chapel. He remained their pastor until his death.
                  See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 117–18; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>,
                  345; Pawson, <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi>, 3:143; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Dictionary</hi>, 108.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
